If the client which has added a user emits the event, then use 

    // sending to all clients except sender
      socket.broadcast.emit(&#39;broadcast&#39;, &#39;hello friends!&#39;);

This will not emit the event to the client and you can have logic in your react app to listen to the socket event as well as the response of the http request.
This will prevent the duplication or bad data.

If there are multiple tabs open for the same client, the client tab which intiated the http request will update the state list with the http response and all other user&#39;s tabs or other users will receive the socket event.

One approach would be to add a &quot;idempotency counter&quot; field in a request. Basically it is just a number, which is incremented for each request, and is stored on a frontend side. Backend would need to answer with the same counter for each successful request.

Your processing logic would look like:
```
function onUserAdded(user, counter) {
  if(current_counter &lt; counter) { 
    console.log(&quot;User added&quot;);
    current_counter++;
  } else {
    console.log(&quot;User not added&quot;);
  }
}
```


- `current_counter=0`
- Call `POST /users`, with `counter = current_counter + 1`, get response with `counter=1` -&gt; `User added`
- Get websocket notification with `counter=1` -&gt; `User not added`

